      "Nebius is Blueprint's contracted artificial intelligence compute holding: a full-stack GPU cloud spanning hardware, networking, storage, orchestration software, and regional datacenters built for training and inference workloads that cannot tolerate hyperscaler queue times. We own Nebius because frontier model laboratories buy dedicated multi-year capacity, and Nebius has signed some of the largest such frameworks publicly disclosed in 2025 and 2026—backlog quality matters more than spot GPU rental headlines.",
      "Microsoft's multi-year agreement carries approximately seventeen point four to nineteen point four billion dollars of potential dedicated capacity over five years. Meta's expanded March 2026 framework totals approximately twenty-seven billion dollars including twelve billion dollars for dedicated GPU clusters from early 2027 on NVIDIA Vera Rubin architecture plus up to fifteen billion dollars for Meta to absorb otherwise-unsold capacity on specified clusters—a take-or-pay structure that reduces merchant exposure. NVIDIA's two-billion-dollar pre-funded warrant investment aligns chip supply with buildout. Filings cite remaining performance obligations on the order of tens of billions of dollars.",
      "Products include dedicated clusters, managed AI cloud services, tooling for distributed training, and a European footprint for sovereignty-sensitive workloads. Nebius emphasizes vertical integration versus bare-metal resellers—software plus hardware plus operations under one contract. Vera Rubin deployments with Meta in 2027 are a visible proof milestone for operational credibility investors will use to judge whether headline signings become energized racks on schedule.",
      "Demand thesis: frontier model competition requires frontier compute; hyperscalers self-build yet still outsource when internal timelines lag customer commitments. Specialist clouds with binding contracts differ from merchant GPU hosts without visibility into utilization. Power procurement for new datacenters links Nebius thematically to our nuclear holdings—compute and electrons are jointly constrained inputs to artificial intelligence scale.",
      "Risks include deployment delays, power and land constraints, customer concentration in Meta and Microsoft, export controls, convertible note financing burden, and eventual GPU normalization as supply expands. Nebius must prove profitable operations at scale, not only contract signings. European operations may benefit from data residency requirements as European Union artificial intelligence regulation pushes workloads to regional infrastructure.",
      "Why we picked Nebius: pick-and-shovel exposure to artificial intelligence infrastructure with multi-year backlog tied to NVIDIA's roadmap—fundamental allocation to the layer beneath applications, selected on contract structure and buildout visibility rather than retrospective equity moves.",
      "We monitor remaining performance obligation growth, cluster deployment cadence, utilization disclosures, capital expenditure versus financing, and Vera Rubin timeline adherence.",
      "Nebius' historical roots in Yandex infrastructure provide operational depth in large-scale systems engineering—relevant when deploying tens of thousands of GPUs with network fabrics that must sustain training jobs measured in weeks. Convertible financing and datacenter capital cycles imply execution risk: backlog converts to revenue only when clusters energize on schedule and customers accept handover. Meta's take-or-pay capacity clause is particularly important—it reduces stranded GPU risk on specified builds compared with pure merchant hosting.",
      "Blueprint grouped Nebius with nuclear holdings conceptually because both address the same artificial intelligence bottleneck from different angles: electrons and flops. We picked Nebius when Microsoft and Meta frameworks provided multi-year visibility rare among public specialist clouds, accepting concentration risk in exchange for contractual clarity.",
      "Managed services atop dedicated clusters—including monitoring, orchestration, and fault tolerance for large training runs—differentiate Nebius from resellers who provide hardware alone. Sovereignty-sensitive European customers may prefer Nebius regions over United States hyperscaler regions for certain workloads, supporting geographic diversification of revenue beyond Meta and Microsoft though those anchors dominate near-term backlog.",
      "Capital intensity is explicit: datacenter buildouts require land, power contracts, and GPU procurement aligned with NVIDIA product transitions. Vera Rubin clusters for Meta in 2027 are the first major post-signing proof point investors can verify against contract headlines. We underwrite Nebius as infrastructure with contracted demand, not as a speculative GPU flip.",
      "Nebius positions against both hyperscaler internal clouds and low-cost GPU resellers by selling reliability and dedicated capacity SLAs frontier labs require. Microsoft and Meta deals imply multi-year visibility into rack energization schedules—reducing the merchant pricing risk that collapsed prior generation hosting businesses when crypto and AI demand cycles diverged.",
      "Software orchestration for fault-tolerant training—checkpointing, network topology, storage bandwidth—is part of the product, not an upsell. Blueprint initiated Nebius when backlog figures and NVIDIA alignment made the specialist cloud category investable at scale; failure would be deployment slippage or customer concentration shocks, not lack of end-market demand for compute.",
      "Remaining performance obligations in filings translate headline contract values into accounting visibility investors can track quarter to quarter—distinct from speculative AI names without contracted backlog. Nebius represents our purest expression of AI infrastructure demand independent of model-layer winner uncertainty.",
      "Convertible note overhang and datacenter capex cycles require monitoring, but contracted Meta and Microsoft frameworks reduce pure merchant GPU exposure relative to prior-generation hosting businesses. European sovereignty positioning may attract workloads as regulators formalize regional AI infrastructure requirements.",
      "We selected Nebius before public markets fully differentiated contracted AI clouds from generic hardware resellers—pick driven by backlog quality, NVIDIA roadmap alignment, and full-stack operational depth.",
      "Dedicated Vera Rubin clusters for Meta starting 2027 tie Nebius revenue to the next NVIDIA product cycle—not prior-generation H100 resale—supporting the thesis that customers contract forward capacity rather than spot-buy aging GPUs. Power and land procurement in new regions remain execution variables we accept as part of infrastructure investing.",
      "Blueprint publishes this Nebius essay as the pre-investment case: contracted AI compute with full-stack delivery, selected when Microsoft and Meta deals made backlog auditable in SEC filings rather than rumored in press alone.",
